{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "The optimal quadrature \"Set A\" with 3 rays per octant, proposed by Carlson (1963), is hard coded, but it is trivial to replace it with whatever other variant is required (see, for example, Jaume Bestard, Štěpán, and Trujillo Bueno, 2021).",
    "The RTE solver computes Q R from three quantities: the mass density, the opacity per mass, and the Planck function.",
    "The latter two must be precomputed by the user (as functions of T and either p or ρ) and stored as lookup tables.",
    "The solver is ignorant of the content of the tables, so it is the user's responsibility to provide physically correct values.",
    "These values may be monochromatic opacities, values of opacity distribution function, or opacities grouped into statistically representative bins (Nordlund, 1982)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "The optimal quadrature \"Set A\" with 3 rays per octant, proposed by Carlson (1963), is hard coded, but it is trivial to replace it with whatever other variant is required (see, for example, Jaume Bestard, Štěpán, and Trujillo Bueno, 2021).",
    "These values may be monochromatic opacities, values of opacity distribution function, or opacities grouped into statistically representative bins (Nordlund, 1982)."
